The '''American Society of Hypertension''' (abbreviated '''ASH''') was an American [[non-profit]] [[professional society]] dedicated to advancing research on [[hypertension]] and related [[cardiovascular disease]]s. ==History== The ASH was founded in 1985 by 17 scientists and physicians.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://rarediseases.org/organizations/american-society-of-hypertension/ |title=American Society of Hypertension |website=NORD (National Organization for Rare Disorders) |language=en-US |access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref> In 2005, the ASH cut ties with the ''[[American Journal of Hypertension]]'' over a dispute over control of content published in the ''Journal''.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=ALDERMAN |first=M |last2=BANES |first2=J |last3=BLUMENFELD |first3=J |last4=GAVRAS |first4=H |last5=KURTZ |first5=T |last6=LARAGH |first6=J |last7=STEINER |first7=S |date=July 2005|title=The American Journal of Hypertension Withdraws from Its Affiliation with the American Society of Hypertension. A Report to Our Readers |url=https://academic.oup.com/ajh/article/18/7/893/220578 |journal=American Journal of Hypertension |language=en |volume=18 |issue=7 |pages=893–893 |doi=10.1016/j.amjhyper.2005.06.003 |issn=0895-7061}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112259517363299394 |title=High Blood Pressure:Doctors Sever Ties With Medical Journal |last=Winslow |first=Ron |date=2005-07-29 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=2018-09-25 |language=en-US}}</ref> In 2006, the society became the center of a dispute over the appropriate role of [[pharmaceutical industry]] in medical research. The dispute prompted several members of an ASH group convened to write a new definition of [[high blood pressure]] to resign from the group; those resigning included former ASH president Michael H. Alderman.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/20/business/20hyper.html |title=Unease on Industry's Role in Hypertension Debate |last=Saul |first=Stephanie |date=2006-05-20 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2018-09-25 |language=en}}</ref> In 2017, the society dissolved and merged with the [[American Heart Association]].<ref>{{Cite press release |title=American Society of Hypertension and American Heart Association to Join Forces to Give a Voice to America's "Silent Killer" |date=2017-07-11 |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/american-society-of-hypertension-and-american-heart-association-to-join-forces-to-give-a-voice-to-americas-silent-killer-300485678.html |language=en |access-date=2018-09-25 |website=www.prnewswire.com}}</ref> The ''[[Journal of the American Society of Hypertension]]'', which was originally the official journal of the ASH, is now affiliated with the AHA.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ashjournal.com/ |title=Homepage |website=Journal of the American Society of Hypertension Website |language=en |access-date=2018-09-25}}</ref>
