'''Cannabis in Dominica''' is a Class B drug to cultivate, sell or possess. This means that possession is punishable by 12 months and $12,000 (summary) or 2 years and $20,000 (on indictment). Supplying, production, or importation are punishable by 3 years and $100,000 (summary) or 14 years and $200,000 (on indictment).<ref>{{citation |url = http://www.dominica.gov.dm/laws/chapters/chap40-07.pdf |title = Drugs (Prevention of Misuse) Act, Chapter 40:07 |format = PDF |date =  |accessdate = 2011-02-17 }}</ref>

In 1995, the US government described Dominica as a minor cannabis producer but "increasingly exploited transit route", with some cannabis cultivated on the island but mostly consumed locally. In 1994 Dominican authorities seized 741&nbsp;kg of cannabis and eradicated 48,855 plants.<ref name="Company1995">{{cite book|author=DIANE Publishing Company|title=International Narcotics Control Strategy Report, 1995|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w0DlWjK3YCEC&pg=PA195|date=1 August 1995|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-0-7881-2057-2|pages=195–}}</ref>

A 2011 report noted that Dominica had large-scale cannabis cultivation for both trafficking and local use, with an estimated 210 acres of cannabis cultivated annually.<ref name="Brownfield2011">{{cite book|author=William R. Brownfield|title=International Narcotics Control Strategy Report: Volume I: Drug and Chemical Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0jnyNWFuhXYC&pg=PA250|date=May 2011|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-1-4379-8272-5|pages=250–}}</ref>

