'''Isaac Chen''' is a [[neurosurgeon]] at the [[Presbyterian Medical Center of Philadelphia]] and the [[Veteran's Administration Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.med.upenn.edu/apps/faculty/index.php/g275/p35031|title=Han-Chiao Isaac Chen - Faculty - About Us - Perelman School of Medicine - Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania|website=Med.upenn.edu|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> The Chen Laboratory works to "develop novel methods for restoring the function of the brain after it has been damaged by combining aspects of stem cell biology, neural tissue engineering, and neural interface technologies."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.med.upenn.edu/chenlab/|title=Homepage - Chen Laboratory - Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania|website=Med.upenn.edu|accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref>
In November 2017 it was reported that a team including Chen has successfully implanted [[brain organoids]] into rodents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statnews.com/2017/11/06/human-brain-organoids-ethics/|title=Tiny human brain organoids implanted in rodents, raising ethical concerns|date=6 November 2017|website=Statnews.com|accessdate=12 November 2017}}</ref>
==Education== He graduated from [[Harvard University]] in 2002 with a BA in Biochemical Sciences followed by a MD from the [[University Of Pennsylvania]] in 2007.
